<section id="intro" class="chapter">
    <h2>1. Introduction: Supply Lines of the Regio Esercito</h2>
    <p>
        Italian transport crews operated across deserts, mountains, and Mediterranean coasts.  
        Despite shortages and difficult terrain, they kept troops supplied in North Africa,  
        the Balkans, and mainland Italy.
    </p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bc/Fiat_626_NLM_Truck.jpg" alt="Fiat 626">
        <p><em>Fiat 626 — Italy’s most important wartime truck.</em></p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="vehicles" class="chapter">
    <h2>2. Vehicles of the Regio Esercito</h2>

    <h3>Fiat 626</h3>
    <p>The workhorse of Italian supply. Reliable but underpowered in mountains.</p>

    <h3>Lancia 3Ro</h3>
    <p>Heavy truck admired for its durability in desert warfare.</p>

    <h3>SPA Dovunque</h3>
    <p>All-terrain vehicle used for mountain transport.</p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/72/Lancia_3Ro_Truck.jpg">
    </div>
</section>

<section id="routes" class="chapter">
    <h2>3. Routes Across the Mediterranean War</h2>

    <h3>North Africa (Libya & Egypt)</h3>
    <p>Loose sand, extreme heat, and dust storms demanded constant maintenance.</p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4a/Italian_Army_North_Africa_Supply.jpg">
    </div>

    <h3>Balkans</h3>
    <p>Narrow mountain roads exposed convoys to guerrilla ambushes.</p>

    <h3>Mainland Italy</h3>
    <p>Steep Apennine passes and Allied air raids made supply work dangerous.</p>
</section>

<section id="safety" class="chapter">
    <h2>4. Safety Protocols & Wartime Discipline</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Low headlights</strong> required after dusk to avoid RAF detection.</li>
        <li><strong>Water rationing</strong> essential in desert campaigns.</li>
        <li><strong>Vehicle camouflage</strong> mandatory when stationary.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="maintenance" class="chapter">
    <h2>5. Field Repairs & Desert Adaptations</h2>
    <p><strong>Sand in carburetors:</strong> Clean with petrol and cloth.</p>
    <p><strong>Tire blowouts:</strong> Use doubled-up inner tubes when spares unavailable.</p>
    <p><strong>Overheated engines:</strong> Wrap radiators with wet cloth at night.</p>
</section>

<section id="life" class="chapter">
    <h2>6. Life of the Italian Driver</h2>
    <p>
        Drivers cooked simple meals of pasta or hard bread, slept beside their trucks,  
        and sometimes bartered with locals for extra supplies.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
        “A truck is a soldier’s last friend in the desert.”
    </blockquote>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/07/Italian_Truck_Convoy_1941.jpg">
    </div>
</section>

